ğŸ¯ Minikube Installation Guide for Ubuntu
This guide provides step-by-step instructions to install Minikube on Ubuntu.
Minikube lets you run a single-node Kubernetes cluster locally for development and testing.

ğŸ“ Pre-requisites
âœ… Ubuntu OS
âœ… sudo privileges
âœ… Internet access
âœ… Virtualization support enabled
Check with:
egrep -c '(vmx|svm)' /proc/cpuinfo
0 = disabled
1 (or more) = enabled

ğŸŸ¢ Step 1: Update System Packages
Update your package lists to get the latest versions:
sudo apt update

ğŸŸ¢ Step 2: Install Required Packages
Install essential packages:
sudo apt install -y curl wget apt-transport-https

ğŸŸ¢ Step 3: Install Docker
Minikube can run Kubernetes in VMs or Docker.
This guide uses Docker as the driver.

Install Docker:
sudo apt install -y docker.io

Enable and start Docker:
sudo systemctl enable --now docker

Add your user to the docker group (to use Docker without sudo):
sudo usermod -aG docker $USER && newgrp docker
Important: Log out (exit) and log back in for this change to take effect.

ğŸŸ¢ Step 4: Install Minikube
Download the Minikube binary:
curl -Lo minikube https://storage.googleapis.com/minikube/releases/latest/minikube-linux-amd64
Make it executable and move it into your PATH:
chmod +x minikube
sudo mv minikube /usr/local/bin/

Verify installation:
minikube version

ğŸŸ¢ Step 5: Install kubectl
Download the latest kubectl:
curl -LO "https://dl.k8s.io/release/$(curl -L -s https://dl.k8s.io/release/stable.txt)/bin/linux/amd64/kubectl"
Make it executable and move it:
chmod +x kubectl
sudo mv kubectl /usr/local/bin/

Verify installation:
kubectl version --client

ğŸŸ¢ Step 6: Start Minikube
Start a Kubernetes cluster using Docker as the driver:
minikube start --driver=docker --vm=true
(Note: You can omit --vm=true if you prefer running purely in Docker.)

ğŸŸ¢ Step 7: Check Cluster Status
Check Minikube status:
minikube status

See your cluster node:
kubectl get nodes

ğŸŸ¢ Step 8: Stop Minikube
Stop the cluster when youâ€™re done:
minikube stop

ğŸŸ¢ (Optional) Delete the Minikube Cluster
Remove the Minikube cluster completely:
minikube delete
âœ… Done!

Youâ€™ve successfully installed Minikube on Ubuntu and can now deploy Kubernetes applications locally for development and testing.

ğŸ‘ Pro Tips
Use minikube dashboard for a built-in Kubernetes dashboard in your browser.
Enable addons (e.g., Ingress) with:
minikube addons enable ingress
Use kubectl for cluster management and deploying workloads.









